ect—revealing the state’s western-style infrastructure to be surprisingly fragile—and a new focus for nativizing discourses which credited traditional Japanese architecture with unique abilities to ride out seismic waves. Tracing his subject from the Meiji Restoration to the Great Kant Earthquake of 1923 (which destroyed Tokyo), Clancey shows earthquakes to have been a continual though mercurial agent in Japan’s self-fashioning; a catastrophic undercurrent to Japanese modernity. This innovative and absorbing study not only moves earthquakes nearer the center of modern Japan change—both materially and symbolically—but shows how fundamentally Japan shaped the global art, science, and culture of natural disaster.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEarthquakesxSocial aspectszJapan. 0aEarthquakeszJapanxPsychological aspects. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aarchitecture.  abuilding codes.  abuilding materials.  abuilding project.  aearthquake safety.  aearthquake science.  aearthquakes.  aecology.  aenvironment.  aenvironmental history.  agreat kant earthquake.  agreat nobi earthquake.  ainfrastructure.  ajapan.  ameiji restoration.  ameiji.  amodern japan.  amodernity.  anation.  anatural disasters.  anonfiction.  aosaka.  ascience.  aseismic activity.  aseismic waves.  aself fashioning.  astructural integrity.  atokyo.  atraditional architecture.  awestern architecture.  awooden building.  awooden structures.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024607240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093229640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932296423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520932296/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  Unive